{"type":"data","nodes":[{"type":"data","data":[{"debug":1},true],"uses":{}},{"type":"data","data":[{"zotero":1,"inscriptions":7,"isBulletin":130},{"title":2,"author":3,"date":4,"citation":5,"uri":6},"Due nuovi saturnii?","Wick","1926","\u003Cspan>F. C. Wick, «Due nuovi saturnii?», \u003Ci>Athenaeum\u003C/i> 4 (1926): 167–71\u003C/span>","https://www.zotero.org/groups/isicily/items/SP2B89MW",[8],{"file":9,"uri":9,"title":10,"status":11,"editionAuthor":13,"type":14,"objectType":18,"material":22,"condition":28,"layoutDesc":29,"handNote":36,"date":50,"places":54,"geo":64,"country":59,"provenance":56,"provenanceGeo":68,"region":71,"settlement":61,"repository":72,"textLang":73,"tmNumber":81,"facsimile":82,"letterHeights":89,"publications":92,"zotero":102,"keywords":112,"html":121,"bibl":122,"bulletinDateSort":127,"citedRangeSort":128,"languageSort":129,"materialSort":23,"typeSort":15},"ISic002753","Fragment of a bilingual dedication to Priapus",{"_":12},"draft",null,{"_":15,"ana":16,"ref":17},"dedication","#function.dedication","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/typeins/lod/88.html",{"_":19,"ana":20,"ref":21},"plaque","#object.plaque","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/259.html",{"_":23,"ana":24,"type":25,"subtype":26,"ref":27},"marble","#material.inorganic.stone.metamorphic_rock.marble","stone.marble","unverified","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/48.html","",{"layout":30},{"_":31,"rs":32,"damage":28},"Five lines of regularly spaced Greek letters followed by three lines of Latin letters. The first two lines of Latin text follow the same spacing as the Greek text; the final line is seemingly centered, more widely spaced (with interpuncts) and separated by a slightly greater interval from the lines above. Although the top of the stone is damaged, the visible space above line 1 is greater than that between the following lines.\n                                    \n                                \t\n\t\t\t",{"_":33,"ana":34,"ref":35},"chiselled","#execution.chiselled","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1",{"lettering":37,"dimensions":38},"Regular, well-cut Greek letters with clearly defined serifs at the end of strokes: Omicron, omega and theta all have rhomboid form; in some instances this is actually a pentagonal form, flat across the top; Omega is open at the bottom; Sigma is four bar and regular; Epsilon has equal horizontal strokes; Alpha has broken bar; the diagonal of the Nu starts and finishes well below/above the ends of the vertical strokes. The Latin letters show the beginnings of the move towards cursive forms: M has extended upper strokes and the midpoint reaches to the bottom of the line; A also has extended upper stroke and lacks a cross-bar; O is rounded, in contrast to the Greek text, as is Q with extended tail; P is open; R is closed; E has short upward slanting strokes; L has a long foot, forming almost a C.",[39,46],{"type":40,"l":41,"from":42,"to":43,"h":44,"unit":45,"atLeast":44,"atMost":44},"letterHeight","Lines 1-8","line1","line8","20","mm",{"type":47,"l":48,"from":42,"to":49,"unit":45},"interlinear","Interlineation\n                                ","line2",{"_":51,"notBefore":52,"notAfter":53},"Late 2nd — 4th century CE",180,400,[55,60],{"_":56,"type":57,"ref":58,"region":59},"Acium","ancient","http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/462067","Sicilia",{"_":61,"type":62,"ref":63,"region":59},"Aci San Antonio","modern","http://sws.geonames.org/2525383",[65],[66,67],37.57533,15.17411,[69,70],37.598818,15.126647,"Sicily","unknown",{"_":74,"mainLang":75,"otherLangs":76,"ana":77,"languages":78},"Ancient Greek and Latin","grc","la","#bilingualism.biversion.complementary",[79,80],"Ancient Greek","Latin","175851",{"n":83,"url":84,"height":85,"width":86,"desc":87,"surfaceType":88},"screen","ISic002753_tiled.tif","2790px","3431px","Scan of photo in NSA 1922 p.494 fig.2","front",[90],{"atLeast":91,"atMost":91},20,[93,94,94,94,94,95,96,97,98,95,99,100,101],"L'année épigraphique: revue des publicatio